The agreement means six companies will now negotiate collectively with unions as an industry under the Chamber's auspices. JOHANNESBURG - The Chamber of Mines says coal producers and unions have agreed to retain a collective bargaining framework for wage talks this year.The National Union of Mineworkers had threatened to go on strike if coal producers pushed ahead with plans to negotiate wages on a company-by-company basis.The agreement means six companies will now negotiate collectively with unions as an industry under the Chamber's auspices.